            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Megan Hanson grew up in a quiet, tree-lined suburb of Minneapolis, the daughter of a practical engineer and a book-loving librarian. From an early age, she was drawn not to the tangible world of her father, but to the stories and images in her mother's library. This led her to pursue an Art History degree at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, a choice her father privately questioned but publicly supported. A transformative internship at the Chicago Art Institute ignited her true passion: not just studying art, but crafting the narrative around it. She discovered a talent for logistics and a sharp eye for creating compelling visual dialogues.\n\nDrawn by its vibrant, iconoclastic arts scene, Megan moved to San Francisco in her late twenties. Her early years were a hustle of gallery assistant jobs, unpaid curatorial work for pop-up shows, and sharing a cramped apartment in the Mission. It was during this time she met and married Kenji Sato, a brilliant software architect. Their marriage was a collision of two worlds\u2014his of data and code, hers of aesthetics and history. Though fond, they were fundamentally different, and they divorced amicably after six years. Megan, by then established in her career, chose to keep the name Sato, a quiet nod to a significant chapter in her life.\n\nNow 41, Megan is the Director of Exhibitions at a prestigious contemporary art museum in SoMa. Her Inner Richmond apartment is her sanctuary, a rent-controlled space filled with books, exhibition posters, and ceramics from local artists. Her daily routine is a familiar comfort: a morning walk in Golden Gate Park followed by the 38R Geary Express bus downtown, a forty-minute journey she uses for reading. Her life is her work and a close-knit circle of friends in the art world. Her dream is to one day curate a career-defining retrospective for a pioneering female video artist she has long admired. Megan feels deeply rooted in San Francisco; it's the city that demanded her grit, honed her vision, and ultimately, allowed her to build a life entirely of her own design."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was 29, standing in a cold Dogpatch warehouse, the air thick with paint fumes and cheap wine. It was her first pop-up show, curated on a shoestring budget and a maxed-out credit card. Seeing strangers stop, really *look*, and discuss the art she had so carefully arranged was a jolt of pure electricity. In that moment, surrounded by borrowed lights and hopeful artists, she felt the first, visceral proof that she could build a world from an idea. That feeling sustained her through years of hustle.\n\n2.\nOn a quiet Tuesday night in their old apartment, Kenji was deep in his world of code while she was lost in a catalogue for a German photographer. He suddenly turned and showed her a data visualization he\u2019d built of foot traffic through her last gallery show \u2013 a pattern of movement she had felt intuitively, now rendered in beautiful, logical lines. It was a moment of profound, parallel affection, a perfect summary of their marriage: two people shepherding their own worlds, side-by-side, speaking different but beautiful languages.\n\n3.\nThe phone call came while she was on her lunch break, eating a salad on a bench in Yerba Buena Gardens. The board offered her the Director of Exhibitions position. After she hung up, she didn\u2019t move. It wasn\u2019t a burst of joy, but a quiet, seismic shift deep within her. The years of assisting, of packing crates, of writing grants, of doubting\u2014they had all just coalesced into this one solid, unshakeable fact. It was the moment she knew she had truly arrived, not just in a job, but in her own life.\n\n4.\nHer father, the practical engineer, flew out for her first major exhibition as Director. He walked through the space slowly, looking not just at the art, but at the lighting, the flow of people, the precise placement of wall text. At the end, near the exit, he turned to her and said, \u201cThis is a very complex system, Meg. You designed it beautifully.\u201d In his own language, he wasn't just seeing her passion; he was finally seeing her craft. That quiet validation healed something in her she hadn't known was still wounded.\n\n5.\nJust last year, on a foggy Saturday morning after a brutal installation week, she walked through Golden Gate Park. The damp air smelled of eucalyptus and earth. As she passed the Conservatory of Flowers, she realized with sudden clarity that she wasn\u2019t lonely, but deeply content. This quiet routine\u2014the walk, the predictable rumble of the 38R, the mug of tea in her own sun-filled apartment\u2014wasn\u2019t a substitute for a different life. It *was* the life, the one she had painstakingly built for herself, and it fit perfectly."
